### Our Interpretation of the GNU Affero General Public License v3

We believe this license provides the best balance between freedom for users and protection for contributors.  
Below is our non-binding interpretation of how we apply the AGPLv3 to Crystal Forge.  
(Quoted terms correspond to defined terms in the license itself.)

1. **Source and Attribution**  
   You must always provide the source code, copyright, and license
   information for Crystal Forge whenever you "convey" any part of it,
   whether verbatim or modified.

2. **Intended Use and Aggregation**  
   Crystal Forge was developed independently and without knowledge of
   your work. Therefore, it should generally be considered a separate
   work when combined with your own software, unless you have modified
   it directly.

   a. If you have *not* "modified", "adapted", or "extended" Crystal Forge,  
      your work is an "aggregate" and not subject to this license.

   b. If you *have* modified, adapted, or extended Crystal Forge,
      those modifications are considered a work "based on" Crystal Forge
      and must remain licensed under the AGPLv3.

3. **Compatibility with Other Licenses**  
   You may freely use Crystal Forge in projects licensed under:
   - the GNU General Public License version 2, or  
   - the GNU Lesser General Public License version 2.1,  
   as these licenses treat Crystal Forge as part of an "aggregate work."

4. **Community and Contact**  
   We welcome all questions and discussions regarding licensing.
   You may contact us at <crystal-forge-support@aicampground.com> or reach the
   Free Software Foundation at <licensing@fsf.org> for guidance.

You can also connect with our community and obtain support through our forum:
<https://crystalforge.us>

---

We hope our interpretation of the AGPLv3 aligns with your own values
and that Crystal Forge proves useful, secure, and empowering for your projects.
Thank you for using and supporting open software.
